<h2>Router</h2>
<p>Declarative client-side routing built on the Navigation API, URLPattern, and <a href="/blocks/view/">ViewEngine</a>. Provides URL-to-view mapping, route parameters, guards, loaders, and prefetching.</p>

<p style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
  <strong>Terminology:</strong> See <a href="/semantics/">Semantics & Glossary</a> for terms like <a href="/semantics/#term-route">route</a>, <a href="/semantics/#term-outlet">outlet</a>, <a href="/semantics/#term-guard">guard</a>, and <a href="/semantics/#term-loader">loader</a>.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
  <strong>Naming note:</strong> The custom element names (<code>&lt;route-view&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;route-outlet&gt;</code>) and attribute names (<code>route:link</code>, <code>route:prefetch</code>) shown below are <em>defaults</em>. Custom element tag names are set at <code>customElements.define()</code> time. Attribute names depend on registration in the <a href="/plugs/webbehaviors/">CustomAttributeRegistry</a>. The <code>route</code>, <code>route:guard</code>, <code>route:loader</code>, and <code>route:error</code> attributes on <code>&lt;template&gt;</code> elements are plain HTML attributes read by <code>&lt;route-view&gt;</code> &mdash; no registry entry needed.
</p>

<h3>Architecture</h3>
<p>Router uses a <strong>hybrid pattern</strong>: components for structural boundaries, behaviors for enhancing existing elements, and plain HTML attributes for declarative metadata.</p>

<table>
  <tr><th>Piece</th><th>Pattern</th><th>Rationale</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>&lt;route-view&gt;</code></td>
    <td>Component (Custom Element)</td>
    <td>Orchestrator that owns child route definitions and renders matched content <strong>in-place</strong>. Child <code>&lt;template&gt;</code> elements are inert; matched content is stamped as children alongside them. The router renders where you define the routes.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>&lt;route-outlet&gt;</code></td>
    <td>Component (Custom Element)</td>
    <td><strong>Named auxiliary views only.</strong> For cases where a route needs to render content to a different area (header, footer, sidebar) outside the <code>&lt;route-view&gt;</code>. Not needed for the primary rendering path.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>&lt;template route="..."&gt;</code></td>
    <td>Plain HTML</td>
    <td>Declarative data read by <code>&lt;route-view&gt;</code>. Guard, loader, error, and outlet attributes are plain HTML &mdash; no classes or registry entries needed. The view component parses them via <code>querySelectorAll</code>.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>route:link</code></td>
    <td>Behavior (CustomAttribute)</td>
    <td>Must preserve native <code>&lt;a&gt;</code> semantics and accessibility. A component would lose the anchor element.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td><code>route:prefetch</code></td>
    <td>Behavior (CustomAttribute)</td>
    <td>Metadata on links. Paired with <code>route:link</code>.</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<p>Router is a <strong>navigation layer</strong> that uses <a href="/blocks/view/">ViewEngine</a> directly:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Router</strong>: URL matching, navigation interception, guards, loaders, scroll restoration, in-place DOM stamping</li>
  <li><strong>ViewEngine</strong>: Hidden modes (for keep-alive cached routes), toggle events, View Transitions</li>
</ul>
<p>Route content doesn't exist in the DOM until the URL matches. No placeholders, no ghost elements. <code>&lt;route-view&gt;</code> stamps matched content as its own children &mdash; the simplest model where the router renders where you define the routes.</p>

